2_1	0.024461436	The 10th U.S.
2_2	0.1512094	Circuit Court of Appeals reversed a 1997 decision by a Wyoming federal judge who ruled that a government wolf reintroduction program in Yellowstone National Park and central Idaho was illegal.
2_3	0.26280781	Ranchers and state farm bureaus oppose the 5-year-old program because they say the wolves endanger livestock.
2_4	0.23908818	They also claim that the program is unnecessary because there is already a viable wolf population in the area.
2_5	0.12045622	The government and environmental groups deny that, and say there may be only a few lone native wolves.
2_6	0.088406497	The groups suing over the program, the American Farm Bureau Federation and state chapters in Wyoming, Montana and Idaho, employed an unusual tactic.
2_7	0.29887899	They pointed out that while native wolves are covered by the Endangered Species Act, the reintroduced wolves are considered part of an ``experimental population'' and can be shot if they threaten livestock.
2_8	0.31885543	The farm groups said the reintroduction program violates the Endangered Species Act by providing different protections to the native and the reintroduced wolves.
2_9	0.12421991	But the appeals court said the 1973 Endangered Species Act and a section added by Congress in 1982 were intended to allow the Interior Department flexibility in its approaches to the goals of preserving and recovering threatened animals.
2_10	0.097523589	The appeals court said a limit to that flexibility ``ignores biological reality and misconstrues the larger purpose'' of the law.
2_11	0.1586023	Environmental groups that joined Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and other government agencies in the appeal of the Wyoming ruling said Thursday's decision sets an important precedent.
2_12	0.22670732	``The practical effect is that the wolves are here to stay,'' said Mark Van Putten, president of the National Wildlife Federation, adding that the decision has ``enormous significance nationwide''.
2_13	0.24294199	Van Putten said there is a thriving population of about 300 wolves in Yellowstone and central Idaho as a result of the reintroduction program.
2_14	0.1386557	Babbitt called the decision ``a ringing endorsement to our wolf reintroduction program''.
